<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06087213 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06087213 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; MEDICAL; SERVICE; OFFICE; PROBE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  San Jose's takeover of its own communications system last year could be addingprecious minutes to the time it takes to notify ambulance crews of medicalemergencies, city Auditor Gerald Silva said in a report issued this week.;   That's because there is no longer an electronic hookup between the people whoanswer 911 emergency lines and medical dispatchers, Silva said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AUDITOR FAULTS SAN JOSE'S MEDICAL EMERGENCYSYSTEM  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;Instead, the fire dispatcher has to telephone the county medicaldispatcher and verbally repeat&quot; the information after the fire department issent to the emergency, Silva's report said.;    Although he cited no specificincidents, Silva said the new system &quot;appears to increase the chances ofmiscommunication or even non-communication&quot; between fire and ambulancedispatchers.;    The fire department, which provides basic rescue andresuscitation services, will also have to wait longer for help from the moremedically sophisticated ambulance crews, Silva's report said.;    &quot;As aresult, San Jose citizens will not receive the advanced life support servicesthe county paramedics provide as quickly as before,&quot; Silva said.;    But SantaClara County dispatchers said the San Jose system is identical to that used byvirtually every city in the county and varies only slightly from the oldsystem.;    &quot;Each (phone) line is separate and specifically labeled,&quot; saidBarbara Jacobson, the county's chief communications dispatcher.;    AlthoughSilva noted that the county had asked that the computer link betweendispatching centers be removed, Jacobson said it was removed because San Josedispatchers are working on a separate computer system at a building miles awayfrom the hilltop county communications center.;    &quot;Typically, betweencenters, you don't find computers that talk to each other,&quot; Jacobson said.&quot;That would really be rare.&quot;;    Bill Collins, the county's administrator ofemergency medical services, provided some of the statistics and otherinformation to Silva's auditors.;    Collins said the auditors' concerns arebased &quot;not so much on the computer but on proximity.&quot; Under the old system,all the dispatchers were in the same room.;    He said that, after talking toauditors, he checked with cities that use the direct phone lines andconcluded, &quot;We haven't really experienced any delays.&quot;;    Silva, who willpresent his report to the city council's finance committee today, said hewants to review ambulance dispatching as part of next year's planned audit ofthe city's communications center.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  MALINE HAZLE, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910327  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  381  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday March 27, 199100087213,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>